text:
Bedrock  is  covered  by  a  variety  of  Pleistocene  to  Recent  sediments  consisting  of 
 yellow Aeolian sands and paler alluvial to lacustrine sands, silts and clays.  Ironstone 
 gravel nodules occur within yellow sands in the northern part of the area. 
 No gold mineralisation ahs been recorded on the property although a cluster of small 
 pits occurs 10 kilometres along strike to the northwest. 
 6.1  PREVIOUS EXPLORATION 
 Nickel  exploration  in  ultramafic  rocks  has  been  reported  by  Jododex  (1972)  and 
 Kennecott  (1972),  although  no  significant  mineralisation  was  located.    Kennecott 
 noted local development of small, copper and silver-bearing limonitic-quartz veins in 
 apparent  felsic  volcanics  in  the  far  north  of  the  area,  although  these  veins  were 
 thought to be of granitic origin.  The last known exploration was carried out by SOG 
 who briefly explored the area for gold in 1993 and 1994. 
 6.2  EXPLORATION BY SOG, 1993/94 
 A  NOAA  image  for  the  area  was  obtained  and  interpreted  by  a  consultant,  Peter 
 Wilson.  A structural interpretation was prepared showing inferred outcrop areas and 
 numerous  faults  or  lineaments.    The  majority  of  these  trend  in  the  northeast  sector 
 although west to northwest trends are also common, particularly in the north of the 
 area.    These  structures  may  or  may  not  have  any  relevance  for  Archaean  gold 
 mineralisation, but have been used for targeting some of the geochemical sampling. 
 A total of 110 soil samples was collected on seven traverses crossing part or all of the 
 greenstone sequence – as interpreted from public domain aeromagnetics and NOAA 
 imagery – within the northern tenement.  These samples were analysed for gold and 
 base metals.  In many areas, transported cover reduced or eliminated the effectiveness 
 of  soil  sampling,  but  in  any  case  no  anomalous  gold  values  were  recorded.
